{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_clover_ver01/data/sn87075277/0034058059A/1958042401/0064.xml":{"full_text":"Page Two\u2014B\nRiglit to Petition\nFor the past 45 years, the initiative and\nreferendum have been guaranteed to the peo\nple of Ohio by their state Constitution. The\npeople themselves wrote the initiative and\nreferendum into their basic law by approving\na constitutional amendment submitted to\nthem by the Constitutional Convention of\n1912.\nThe initiative and referendum is an in\nstrumentation of the earlier guarantee of the\nright of petition by the Constitution of the\nUnited States. Even Congress may not inter\nfere with the people's light of petition.\nAny attempt to interfere with the circu\nlation of petitions is an assault upon one of\nthe basic rights of the people and is thorough\nly reprehensible. If a majority of the people\nare opposed to the subject matter of any con\nstitutional amendment or law proposed by\npetitions, they will have the opportunity to\nregister their opposition at the polls. But the\nright to obtain signatures for a popular vote\nOil any issue should at all times be protected.\nYet, at the present time there is evidence\nthat opponents of the so-called Right-to-Work\nAmendment to the Constitution of Ohio are\nseeking to impede the circulation of petitions\nfor the proposed amendment through implied\nthreats of reprisals and intimidating pres\nsures.\nOffers ftewards\nAbout this time of the year it is well to\nurge ali our readers to consider the possible\npleasure to be obtained from flowers, fruits\nand vegetables. It is also worth noting that,\nsometimes, such activity can develop a mone\ntary profit.\nWe are not much concerned in this arti\ncle, with the economic gains of gardenir^g.\nThere are other values that come to the in\ndividual who seeks to develop something of\nbeauty and perfection in accordance with the\nlaws of nature.\nThere are countless homes in Noble\ncounty on lots that need the charm that can\nCommunity Needs\nAny community in the United States, in\ncluding Caldwell, can make progress when\never the majority of its inhabitants are more\ninterested in the general welfare than in en\nvying their neighbors.\nThe population of any given area, united\nin common advantages, facing the same dis\nadvantages and seeking methods of growth,\ncan assess its prospects upon the basis of its\naverage inhabitant.\nIt takes more than natural resources to\nmake a properous people. This applies to na\ntions, states, counties, and municipalities. The\nspirit of the people, within certain physical\nboundary lines, is more important to the wel\nfare of the people than the possession of cer\u00ad\nTHE \"RECESSION\"\nBy Willis E. Stone\nThe promotion and manage\nment of the current \"recession\"\nby Washington politicians\nmakes no sense at all! This is\nnot necessarily a new condi\ntion, but it is one which has\nreached alarming proportions.\nLet's analyze it a moment.\nWe have been told we must\npay high taxes because our\nown money in our own hands\nto buy the tilings we individ\nually want would be \"infla\ntionary.\"\nLarge portions of our tax\ndollars are then used to put\nbureaucrats into direct com\npetition with tax paying enter\nprises. The bureaucrats, how\never, have the unique advant\nage of operating interest free,\nrent free, cost free and tax\nfree, charging their losses and\nhidden costs back to the tax\npayers.\nWe are told that other por\ntions of our tax dollars must\nbe given to socialistic and com\nmunistic nations throughout\nthe world to keep these soc\ncialistic and communistic na\ntions from going socialistic and\ncommunistic.\nOur tax dollars syphoned\ninto foreign countries are used\nto develop industrial produc\ntion by subjugated labor. To\nhelp these \"poorer\" nations we\nhave given free access to our\ndomestic markets.\nIndeed we have done more\n\u2022mi\nHave you met Tony yet? He's\nfrom Europe\u2014and rents the old\nWhalen farm.\nTony's a good worker and has\nthat farm running pretty slick.\nFunny though on days otf\u2014Tony\nhangs around the barbershop\nlistening to the political discus\nsions. But he never says a word.\nLast Thursday, though, Tony\nwas there and was speaking his\nrund. When I asked him about\nthe sudden change, he smiled\nf.nd showed a brand-new set of\ncitizenship papers. \"Now I talk\nEDITORIAL PAGE\nCOVERS NoBui\u00a3ouNTy i t-^-E SuNf-uiN-z\nTiie American Way\nthan that. We are restricting\nthe planting of cotton while\nproviding funds for other\ncountries to go into cotton pro\nduction. We have priced our\ncotton out of the world market\nby political \"subsidies\" and\n\"support programs.\" We are\ndoing the same thing in a score\nof other basic products.\nWe are compelling sugar\nfarmers to curtail their crops\nand stop exporting. We have\neven outlawed the production\nof sugar in America in excess\nof 54 percent of our domestic\nconsumption to insure a half\nbillion dollar a year American\nmarket for foreign sugar pro\nduction, managed by a sugar\ncartel.\nAbout 40 percent of the re\ntail price of American made\nautomobiles goes to taxes, but\nforeign made car-.! are heavily\nsupported by indirect subsidies\nof American tax dollais, and\nenjoy free access to the Ameri\ncan market through almost\nnon-existent import duties.\nThese are a few of the poli\ntical reasons for unemploy\nment. These conditions being\nso patently true it would seeni\nthat Washington politicians\nwould be the first to recognize\nthe fact that, by reversing the\nprocess which produced the\n\"recession\" we would have it\nwhipped before it even started.\nBureaucrats, however, make\nthe \"recession\" an instrument\nfor justifying further plunder-\nFrom where I sit... iy Joe Marsh\nTurnabout a la Tony\nup like an American should,\" he\nsaid.\nFrom where I sit, every citi\nzen has a right to speak his mind\non all subjects. For instance, I\nhappen to feel that beer is just\nabout the best refreshment bev\nerage there is. Nobody has to\nagree with\nmy\nchoice\u2014but there's\nno arguing my right to \"sound\noff\" about it.\nCopyright, 1958, United Status Brtwcrs FoartdMufH\nThe proposed amendment would outlaw\ncompulsory labor union membership. The\npressure being exerted on circulators of pe\ntitions for the amendment is being traced to\nunion bosses and misguided zealots who do\nnot want the issue to come to a popular vote.\nThe opponents of the amendment will\nhave plenty of time before the proposed vote\non the issue in November to campaign against\nit, openly, freely and forcefullly. They do not\nhave the right to harass the circulators of\npetitions for the amendment.\nSuch tactics are goon tactics. They seek\nto substitute force for freedom of expression.\nThey attempt to repress a basic rignt of the\npeople.\nDuring the 45 years they have had the\nright of initiative and referendum, the vot\ners of Ohio have adopted numerous consti\ntutional amendments and they have rejected\nmany proposed amendments.\nLet the people speak on the Right-to\nWork Amendment. To that end, let the peti\ntions be freely circulated. We hope there will\nbe such a revulsion against the tactics being\nused to suppress the petitions that many more\nvolunteers will step forward to circulate them\nand that there will be a flood of signatures\nreasserting the people's basic rights.\nOhio State Journal\ncome only from well-appointed surrounds. It\nmay take some years to develop an attractive\nlawn or garden, but the task will bring satis\nfaction, however long delayed. Besides, what\nyou do with your lot will add to the natural\nbeauty of your town.\nWhen it comes to vegetable gardening,\none must admit that the process involves\nwork. At the same time, many business mep\nwould be\nphysically\nbenefitted\nby\ncise. We know, from hearing them boast, that\nthe amateur gardeners take as much delight\nin their prize specimens as fishermen who\ntalk so much about the \"one that got away\".\ntain assets which are often deemed advanta\ngeous.\nYou can give a locality an excellent cli\nmate, wonderful natural resources and an in\ndustrial set-up that is efficient, but, unless\nyou can breathe a common purpose into the\nlife of the area, it will fall far short of be\ncoming highly properous.\nsome exer\u00ad\nThis does not mean that some few citi\nzens may not be able to milk the area for\ntheir benefit, and become rich. It does mean\nthat the area as a whole, and its inhabitants,\ncannot become prosperous. Great wealth,\nside by side with abject poverty, does not\nmake an ideal communitv.\nAitrertUrmrnt\ning of the public purse. They\npropose to \"spend\" us into\nprosperity.\nHow much simpler it would\n\u2022be if government would stop\ncompeting with the private\nenterprises of its own taxpay\niijg citizens under the pre\ntense of taking care of them.\nThis would restore our tradi\ntional principle of equity and\njustice. Producers would be\nble to enjoy the product of\ntheir toil and spend their own\nmoney for the things they\nwish, making more jobs for\nmore people.\nGetting government out of\ncompetition with its own citi\nzens would so tremendously\nCUt the cost of government that\nwe could abolish the individual\nincome tax menace, increase\nthe take-home pay and raise\nthe purchasing power of the\nAmerican people by about 20\npercent. This would px-oduce\nthe greatest economic pros\nperity in all of history and\nrestore our dynamic American\nfree enterprise system.\nShall we restore our econ\nomic health in this manner or\nshall we permit bureaucracy to\ntake over our property, destroy\nOur economy, inflate our\nmoney and establish a total\ncontrol over everything and\neverybody?\nGermany tried to solve a\n\"recession\" by inflating the\ncurrency and produced a Hit\nler. Italy tried to cure a \"re\ncession\" by developing the\n\"corporate state\" and produced\na Mussolini.\nHere in the United States we\ncan return to the tried and\ntrue \"American Way\" by out\nlawing the alien practice of\ngovernment competition with\nprivate enterprise and repeal\ning the Marxist income tax by\ngetting action on a \"proposed\n23rd Amendment\" pending in\nCongress as H. J. Res. 355. It\nprovides that:\nSec. 1. The Government of\nthe United States shall not en\ngage in any business, profes\nsional. commercial, financial\nor industrial enterprise except\nas specified in the Constitution\nSec. 4. Congress shall not\nlevy taxes on personal incomes,\ninheritances and/or gifts.\nPhoto Developing\u2014Gillespie's\nFOR\nCONGRESS\nDemocratic Primary\nTHE JOURNAL, CALDWELL, OHIO\nThe body of Pfc. William S.\nEagon, son of Mr. and Mrs. W. G.\nEagon, of the Batesville com\nmunity, arrived at Quaker City,\nMonday night.\nDr. Viola Startzman, only\ndaughter of Mr. and Mrs. II. J.\nStartzman, Main street, will\nbroadcast on the Child Health\nprogram, over station WJW,\nCleveland, Saturday afternoon,\nMay 1, at 12:35 o'clock.\nThe mercury reached a new\nhigh of 91 degrees in Noble\ncounty last Monday to set a\nrecord, not topped for the past\nten years. This record was avail\nable at the office of Frank Bur\nlingame, of Sharon.\nTesta Excavating Co., of Cald\nwell and Cleveland, engaged in\nstrip mining operations in Aure\nlius township, bordering Noble\nand Washington counties, be\ncame a defendant, Tuesday, in\nanother lawsuit resulting from\nE A E I A N W A Y\n60IN6\nSOMETHING\nFront Journal Files\nTen Years Ago\nWilliam Edward Singleton. 22\nmonth-old son of Mr. and Mrs.\nEverett W. Singleton, of Seneca\nville route 1, in northeastern\nNoble county, drowned Monday\nafternoon in Possum creek, near\nthe home of his parents.\nMiss Gladys Pakes, daughter\nof Mr. and Mrs. Andy Pakes, of\nSanta Monica, California, for\nmerly of Belle Valley, was\nnamed Queen of Industry to\nreign over the second Santa\nMonica Bay Industries Show,\nheld April 26, 27 and 28 in the\nwest.\nMrs- H. H. Birch, nee Jean\nFrakes, of Caldwell, left this\nweek for Seattle, Washington,\nfrom which port she will sail\nfor Tokyo, Japan, to join her\nhusband, Captain H. H. Birch,\npublic information officer with\nthe United States Army.\nJimmie C. Flood, of Beaver\ntownship, Noble county, is the\nnumber one veteran in the state\nof Ohio, He received his bonus\ncheck in the amount of $220.00.\nA thirty-two car Pennsylvania\nfreight train, traveling north,\nwas wrecked in the tunnel at\nAva, adjacent to the Ava Brick\nPlant at 9:00 o'clock, Saturday\nmorning. Several cars left the\ntrack, inside the tunnel, result\ning in a delay of approximately\n12 hours.\nConsider all three price,\nquality and outstanding repu\ntation for longer-lasting beauty.\nWhen you do, you will come up\nwith a single answer: Sherwin\nWilliams SWP1 Huuse Paint is\nthe best buy. When you use\nSWP on your house you'll be a\nmighty happy homeowner!\nFLO*\nAND\n\u00a3NAM\u00a3L\nHOW ABOUT\nm&N i\nATTEND\nBOARfc\nMEETING?\nSuggestion: DO-IT-YOURSELF!\nLinda, six-year-nld daughter of\nMr. and Mrs. Herschei Jordan,\ntell at her home on North street,\nThursday, fracturing her left arm\nat the elbow.\nMiss Mary Ann Shafer and\nMiss Janet Pickenpaugh were\nnamed co-valedictorians of the\n1348 graduating class of the\nCaldwell high school.\nNoble County\nSoil Conservation\nDistrict\nNews\nWalter T. Crum has been\nworking on drainage problems\non Little Creek near Ashton Inn.\nHe's removed he bush and\ntrees that causes the stream to\nchange direction and by using\nhis crawler tractor, he's straigh\ntening the channel that took a\nlot of bottomland out of produc\ntion.\nWater from across the road\ncomes through culverts and is\ntaken to the stream in a new\nsod waterway and two open\nditches. On the other side of\nthe stream, 900' of 4\" drain\ntiie is being installed to drain\nout a seep area that has always\ngiven Walter trouble. And in\nthis case no land is being taken\nout of production.\nI have seen notices lately that\nindicate this may be a dry year.\nLocal district cooperators are\ninterested in the affect this will\nhave on spring flow. Reports\nshow that some U. S. Weather\nBureau stations in the state hav\nonly had .58 of an inch of rain\nor snow, the highest was 1.66 3'r\nthe month of March. Total rain\nfall for January, February and\nMarch averaged only 3.97 inches\nless than half the normal\npected rainfall for the period\nThis is the part of the year thai\ngenerally contributes the mo.,t\nof our ground water storagt\nsupply.\nIt cannot be stored without\nthe rainfall and subsequent in\nfiltration and percolation to tin\nground water table. Water tables\nwere generally lower at the en\n\u2022f Maivh than the :,t .it\nYour kesf buy in\nhouse\npaint!\nHouse pain\u00bb\nAvailable in\nGallon\nQuantities.\nFOR BEAUTIFUL FLOORS, PORCHES,\nSTEPS AND DECKS USE\nSHERWIN-WILLIAMS\nPORCH AND FLOOR ENAMEl\nDONALD D. NICHOLS\n\"1U\u00a3 B\u00a3SI rOR LESS\"\n\u00a3|ioiie 63-J 506 Cumberland Street\nTHIS WEEK\nIN\nWASHINGTON\nREP. JOHN E. HENDERSON\nA Bold Challenge\nBy the time this column ap\npears, I am sure there will have\nbeen many analyses of President\nEisenhower's proposal for re\norganizing the Defense Depart\nment. His recommendations are\nfar reaching and, in the minds\nof many persons, even drastic.\nHowever they are received in\nvarious quarters, there is agree\nment that they are a marked de\nparture which will not be accept\ned without a tremendous struggle.\nWe are beginning to witness an\nundercurrent of opposition which\nhas no apparent source, and\nwhich has no apparent sense of\ndirection, designed to counteract\nthe proposal which the President\nhas made. A powerful force, such\nas our military, has always ex\nerted a very substantial pressure\nupon national affairs. In one way\nor another, the Pentagon main\ntains an elaborate machine for in\nfluencing public opinion and ap\nplying direct pressure upon Capi\ntol Hill. The present recom\nmendations are sure to touch off\nfight, the like of which the\nnation has not witnessed since\nthe unification battles following\nWorld War II.\nOther Presidents acting in their\ncapacity of Commander-in-Chief\nhave endeavored in the past to\nmake radical changes in the mili\ntary setup, only to find that their\nefforts met with a strong wall of\nopposition. Resistance to change\nwill be generated as the Presi\ndent's plan to destroy duplication\nand satin-lined empires is under\nstood. The task ahead will require\nthe skill, knowledge, and under\nstanding of a great military com\nmander, and President Eisen\nhower will find use for all of the\nresources that he possesses in the\nhurculean crusade upon which\nhe has embarked.\nWhatever feelings we may\nhave about the specific proposals,\nthere is a strong feeling of agree\nment that the new plan is moti\nvated by a sense of urgency and\ndeep sincerity of purpose. The\nrevolution in weapons and future\nwarfare is clearly challenging our\nconcepts of both time and space.\nHow we meet this issue will\ndetermine our national security\nas much, and possibly more than\nall of the billions we have poured\ninto our military programs. One\nthing is sure we cannot ignore\nthe flood tide of technological\nchanges and assume that no\nchange in our defense structure\nis required! How quickly we can\nreact as a nation may be the\nmeasure of our national survival\nand as precious as all of the ad\nvanced weapons man's inventive\ngenius has created. The problem\nnow frtrinr is how to *tr*nr\nWORRY-FREE\n-T\nKOON HOLLER\nInflation\nOnce upon a time a man raising his own hogs needed corn to\nfeed them so he bargained to work for a farmer one day a week, ine\nfarmer gave him $5.00 for the days work which he in turn gave bacK\nto the farmer for corn at $1.00 per bushel, netting him five bushels\nof corn.\nAfter a time he said to the farmer, \"From now on I want six\ndollars a day for my work.\" The farmer replied, \"O.K., I'll have to\nhave more money for my corn. From today on, corn will cost you\n$1.20 per bushel.\"\nThen one day the laborer said, \"I want $7.50 a day for my\nThe farmer paying the increased wage also raised the corn to $1.5,0\nper bushel.\nTime after time the laborer raised his wage until he received\n$10.00 per day. At the same time the price of his corn was raised to\n$2.00 per bushel. Not withstanding the several raises in his wage, he\nstill took home five bushels of corn for his day's work.\nWhile the laborer received twice the original wage and the\nfarmer twice as much for his corn, neither one was ahead in the\ngame.\nThis game of economic leap-frog is also called inflation.\nThe basic cause of inflation is scarcity and the willingness of\nthe people to pay exorbitant prices. Scarcity in Our Way of Life is\ncaused by government meddling. All America needs is more sound\nbusiness in government and less government in business. Set at\nliberty the creative forces oi' individualism and business, and in a\nfortnite the dangers of inflation will vanish.\nthat virtually instant action is\npossible without jeopardizing the\nsystem of popular government\nwhich must remain the master\nof our military establishment. The\nanswer is not easy, and the\nPresident's proposals outline one\npossible direction. Whether there\nare alternatives which are as ef\nfective remains to be seen.\nThe Battle of the Capitol\nFront\nOne of the controversies that is\nraging in Washington these days\narises from the decision to extend\nthe front of the Capitol building\nan additional 35 feet at a rather\nsubstantial cost. Two of the news\npapers here .re keeping the mem\nbers of Congress abreast of all\nof the arguments that the edi\ntorial writers can devise. The\nmorning paper has hotly dis\nagreed with the extension plan,\nwhile one of the evening papexs\nis favoring the extension with\nequal enthusiasm. One group in\nsists that the Capitol is a monu\nment and should not be changed\nin any way that the thousands\nof school children who come to\nWashington annually expect to\nsee the Capitol untouched and\nunmarred.\nThe fact of the matter is that\nthe front of the Capitol is deter\niorating because of the soft stone\nwith which it was constructed.\nThe deterioration has not been\nslowed by expensive periodic\npainting. The group who favor\nthe expensive extension point out\nthat, inasmuch as money is going\nto have to be expended to pre\nserve the Capitol, it may as well\nbe a useful expenditure to pro\nvide additional interior space\nwhile the preservation process is\ngoing on.\nThe Speaker of the House, who\nis head of the Commission on the\nextension of the Capitol, has in\ndicated that the extension will\nmove forward. His decision is\nbeing cheered and jeered with\nabout equal fervor.\nInasmuch as the structure of\nthe Cnpitol hns beert morHficd\nmany, many times since the i i\nNew CITY LOAN\nanjd\nAt No Extra Cost\nWANT A FINE NEW OR US1D CAR\n...APPLIANCES OR OTHER THINGS?\nJUST ASK YOUR DEALER FOR NEW\nCITY LOAN INSURED FINANCING.\nHERE'S WHY:\nS\n520 West Street Phone 69\nBob Miller, Manager\nFIRST... you get the low-cost terms and easy\npayments you want from your dealer in a jiffy*\nSECOND... your account is automatically in\nsured through The Prudential Insurance Co. AT\nNO EXTRA COST TO YOU.\nTHIRD... IN CASE OF DEATH YOUR DEBT\nIS CANCELED AND YOUR UNPAID\nBALANCE IS PAID IN FULL AT\nONCE.\nFOURTH...no matter where you go to buy\nin Ohio, The City Loan is nearby which means\nfast action and quick delivery on any purchase\nyou make.\nThursday, AprU_2V95S\nUncle Sam Stille\nla\u00b0or-\ncornerstone was laid by George\nWashington, it. is inconceivable\nto me that we can expect that\nthere will be no. changes made to\nthe building in the next 150 years\nof its existence.\nAlthough I do not wholeheart\nedly agree that it is necessary to\nchange the dimensions of the\nCapitol at this time, I am fairly\nconfident that anyone seeing it\ninfrequently would scarcely be\nable to discover any of the pro\nposed changes since its main\npoint of recognition is the fam\niliar heavy, dominating dome.\nEven the dome seemed not to\nbe sufficient for recognition by\none chap who stopped me on the\nstreet recently and, in all sin\ncerity, pointed to the Capitol and\nasked me if 1 could be so kind\nas to tell him what the building\nwas. Frankly, I was a little stun\nned, and then I thought perhaps\nhe was a little bit of a joker, but\nafter looking at his serious, in\nquiring face, I am convinced\nthat he really did not know that\nhe was looking at the Capitol of\nthe United States.\n,cr\nIF YOU EVER HAVE TROUSUf\nWITH YOUR TELEVISION SET...\n\u2014get in touch with us. We can\nfind the difficulty quickly\u2014fix\nit promptly and reasonably. Our\nservicemen are trained in the\nlatest television techniques par-'\nticularly as they apply in this\narea.\nCALDWELL TV SERVICE\n410 Spruce Street Phone 44\nCaldwell, Ohio\nwe recommend\n'J I'NG SOL Radio and TV Tubes\nSo go ahead and buy a ear or whatever you\nneed. Enjoy your purchase without worries\u2014\ntiie City Loan insured way. Just say to your\ndealer \"City Loan insured financing please!\"\nThat makes it a real deal, in your favor.\numma\navings ompany\nOffice* All Over Ohio Financing Ohioans Since 1912\nCaldwell, Ohio","height":"27129","width":"21366"}}
